Welcome to notebook nine of the Java track. Notebook eight introduced Spring Core, the container that owns your beans and wires them together. This notebook turns that container into a network facing service. Spring Web is where Spring stops being a clever library for objects in memory and becomes the most popular way in the world to build a hypertext transfer protocol back end.

Here is the map for what we will cover. First, the Spring m v c request flow, with the dispatcher servlet at the centre. The distinction between at sign Controller and at sign Rest Controller, and when to use each. The h t t p method mappings, including at sign Get Mapping, at sign Post Mapping, at sign Put Mapping, at sign Delete Mapping, and at sign Patch Mapping. The parameter level annotations for extracting request data, including at sign Path Variable, at sign Request Param, at sign Request Body, and at sign Request Header. How responses get returned, including just returning a value, using at sign Response Status to change the default code, and returning a Response Entity for full control. Automatic JSON serialisation and deserialisation via Jackson. Validation with at sign Valid and the bean validation annotations like at sign Not Blank, at sign Size, and at sign Email. Centralised error handling with at sign Controller Advice and at sign Exception Handler. Returning standardised error responses with Problem Detail, which implements r f c seventy eight oh seven. Calling other services with Rest Client, the modern synchronous client, and Web Client, its reactive cousin. The essentials of Spring Security, including the security filter chain, authentication, and authorisation. Method level security with at sign Pre Authorize and at sign Post Authorize. And finally, c o r s in one paragraph.

Let us start with how a request actually flows through Spring m v c. Every incoming hypertext transfer protocol request lands in the same front controller, called the dispatcher servlet, which Spring Boot wires up automatically. From the dispatcher servlet, the request goes through a handler mapping, which picks the right controller method by examining the u r l and the h t t p verb. Then through a handler adapter, which resolves the method's arguments by inspecting their parameter annotations, like at sign Path Variable and at sign Request Body. Then into your controller, which runs the business logic and returns a value. After your controller returns, optional handler interceptors can run pre and post hooks, and an optional response body advice can shape the response further. Finally, the value is converted into a hypertext transfer protocol response by a message converter, with Jackson handling JSON serialisation by default.

You almost never touch the inner pieces directly. Spring Boot's auto configuration assembles a working pipeline at startup. Your job is to write controller classes. The framework wires them into the flow.

Two stereotype annotations, two different purposes. The at sign Controller annotation is for server side views. Method return values are interpreted as view names, like the name of a Thymeleaf template or a j s p file. This is the classic web app style. The at sign Rest Controller annotation is for r e s t application programming interfaces. Method return values are interpreted as the response body itself, serialised to JSON. At sign Rest Controller is just at sign Controller plus at sign Response Body applied to every method, as a single convenient annotation. For modern services that talk JSON, at sign Rest Controller is the only stereotype you will use.

You combine at sign Rest Controller with at sign Request Mapping at the class level to give all methods in the controller a common base path. Then on each method, you use one of the five h t t p method shortcut annotations. At sign Get Mapping, at sign Post Mapping, at sign Put Mapping, at sign Delete Mapping, and at sign Patch Mapping. Each of those is a shortcut for at sign Request Mapping with the corresponding method argument. Use the shortcuts. They read better than the verbose form.

Each parameter level annotation pulls a different piece of the incoming request and maps it to a method parameter. At sign Path Variable extracts a templated segment from the u r l, like the id in the path slash users slash open curly id close curly. At sign Request Param pulls a value from the query string, like page and size in the query question mark page equals zero ampersand size equals twenty. You can also give at sign Request Param a default value, which is what you usually want for paging parameters. At sign Request Body deserialises the request body from JSON into the parameter type. At sign Request Header pulls a value from an h t t p header. At sign Cookie Value pulls a value from a cookie. And if you ever need full control over the raw request, you can declare an Http Servlet Request parameter with no annotation, and Spring will hand you the raw thing.

JSON conversion is automatic. Spring Boot bundles Jackson, the most widely used JSON library on the java virtual machine. Jackson serialises any return value to JSON. Jackson deserialises every at sign Request Body parameter from JSON. Records are the ideal shape for request and response data transfer objects, because Jackson handles records by component name out of the box, with no setters required. Use records for d t o s by default.

There are three ways to control what comes back from your controller. In order of how often you will use each. The first way is to just return the value. Spring sets two hundred ok as the status, serialises the return value to JSON, and writes it to the response body. The second way is to put at sign Response Status on the method, with the status you want as the default. The most common case is at sign Response Status of h t t p status dot CREATED for a post handler that creates a resource. The third way, for full control, is to return a Response Entity wrapper. Response Entity gives you fluent methods for setting the status, the headers, and the body in a single return value. Use it when you need control over headers, or when the status varies based on what the method computed.

For deletion handlers that succeed silently, use at sign Response Status of h t t p status dot NO underscore CONTENT, which is two hundred four, and declare the method's return type as void. This is the conventional shape for a delete endpoint.

Do not accept whatever the client sends. Validate at the controller boundary so bad input never reaches your service layer. Spring integrates with Jakarta Bean Validation, the j s r three eighty standard. You annotate the data transfer object once, and you add at sign Valid to the parameter in the controller signature. Common constraints worth knowing. At sign Not Null requires a non null value. At sign Not Blank requires a non null, non empty, non whitespace string. At sign Not Empty requires a non null collection or array with length greater than zero. At sign Size with min and max constrains the length or size. At sign Min and at sign Max constrain numeric values. At sign Positive and at sign Negative require positive or negative numeric values. At sign Email requires a valid email address. At sign Pattern with a regexp argument requires the string to match a regular expression.

When validation fails, Spring throws a method argument not valid exception. By default this becomes a four hundred bad request response. The default error body is not great, however. To shape it nicely, you use centralised error handling, which is the next topic.

Without help, every exception thrown out of a controller becomes a generic five hundred internal server error, with the stack trace exposed to the client. You want the opposite. Domain exceptions should map to specific h t t p statuses, with a clean, machine readable response body. The mechanism is a single class annotated at sign Rest Controller Advice. Inside that class, you write methods annotated at sign Exception Handler, each one taking a specific exception type as its parameter.

Spring picks the most specific exception handler for each thrown type. A domain exception like User Not Found Exception maps to four hundred four. A validation exception maps to four hundred. A generic exception handler at the bottom logs the error and returns a five hundred response with no internal details exposed.

The right shape for the error response body is Problem Detail, which implements r f c seventy eight oh seven, the standard JSON shape for h t t p error responses. The default Problem Detail body has type, title, status, detail, and instance fields. You can add custom fields with the set Property method. Using Problem Detail makes your error responses self describing and interoperable with any client that understands the standard.

A single rest controller advice class catches exceptions thrown from any controller in the entire application. You do not need one per controller. One global advice with a handler per exception type is the standard pattern.

For making h t t p calls out of your service to other services, Spring Framework six point one, which ships in Spring Boot three point two, introduced the Rest Client. Rest Client is a fluent, synchronous client that replaces the older Rest Template. Use it for typical service to service calls. You configure a Rest Client bean once in a configuration class, with a base u r l and any default headers. You inject that bean into your gateway class, and you call the fluent methods to issue requests. Get to set the verb. U r i to set the path. Retrieve to send the request. Body to deserialise the response.

Rest Client is the new default for blocking h t t p calls. It looks like normal blocking code, which is exactly right when you are running on virtual threads from notebook six. You get high concurrency without the cognitive load of reactive chains.

The reactive cousin of Rest Client is called Web Client. Web Client has the same fluent builder, but it returns Mono of t or Flux of t reactive types instead of plain values, and it integrates with Project Reactor for non blocking streams. Use Web Client only if you have committed to a reactive stack, which means you are also using Spring WebFlux instead of Spring m v c. For everything else, Rest Client is the right answer.

Now, the essentials of Spring Security. Adding the dependency Spring Boot starter security to your project gives every endpoint h t t p basic authentication by default. Secure by default, even if you do not write any security configuration. To shape that behaviour, you define a security filter chain bean.

The security filter chain bean takes an Http Security builder, configures it through a fluent application programming interface, and returns the built chain. Inside the configuration, you specify which u r l patterns require authentication, which roles are needed for which patterns, and which authentication mechanism to use. C s r f protection is enabled by default. For a stateless JSON application programming interface, you typically disable it explicitly, because c s r f is a browser based attack vector that does not apply to token authenticated machine to machine traffic.

The authorize h t t p Requests method takes a lambda that lets you list authorisation rules in priority order. First match wins. Request matchers takes a path pattern and optionally an h t t p method. The permit All method allows anyone. The authenticated method requires any authenticated user. The has Role method requires a specific role. The h t t p basic method, with the with Defaults helper, enables h t t p basic authentication. For browser apps with login forms, swap that for form Login. For JSON web token protected apis, swap that for o auth two Resource Server.

Two important supporting beans complete the picture. The User Details Service is Spring's lookup mechanism for usernames and credentials. You implement it, or you use one of the built in implementations, to load credentials from your database. The Password Encoder bean is critical for storing passwords. Never store plain text passwords. B Crypt Password Encoder is the standard choice.

Per endpoint rules in the filter chain handle coarse grained authorisation. For fine grained checks, like only the owner of this account can delete it, use method security annotations directly on your service or controller methods. To enable method security, annotate a configuration class with at sign Enable Method Security.

The at sign Pre Authorize annotation runs before the method executes. Denied calls never execute. The at sign Post Authorize annotation runs after the method executes. It is useful when the authorisation check depends on the value the method returns. Both annotations take a string argument, which is a Spring Expression Language expression. The expression can reference the method's arguments, the authenticated user, and in the case of at sign Post Authorize, the return value.

Spring Expression Language is the embedded expression engine used throughout Spring. In a security expression, you can write has Role of some role, to require a specific role. You can use hash sign followed by a parameter name, to reference a method parameter by name. You can use the authentication variable to refer to the authenticated user, with authentication dot name for the username. You can use the return Object variable, only in at sign Post Authorize, to refer to the value the method returned. The full Spring Expression Language is large, but for security expressions, those four building blocks cover most needs.

Finally, c o r s in one paragraph. C o r s stands for cross origin resource sharing. If your front end lives at a different origin than your back end, for example a browser application served from app dot example dot com calling an application programming interface at api dot example dot com, the browser enforces c o r s rules and will refuse to send the request unless your server explicitly allows the origin. Spring lets you configure c o r s globally with a Web m v c Configurer bean, per controller or per method with the at sign Cross Origin annotation, or inside the security chain with the dot c o r s method. For most cases, a single global configuration is the right move. List the allowed origins, the allowed methods, and the allowed headers, and apply it across the whole application programming interface.

That wraps notebook nine. You can now expose a service over hypertext transfer protocol with the right shapes. Validated requests. Type safe responses. Standardised error responses. Outbound calls to other services. And authenticated, authorised access. Combined with the inversion of control and dependency injection patterns from notebook eight, this is the bulk of what a Spring microservice actually does at runtime.

Notebook ten plugs in the data layer with Spring Data. We will look at Java persistence application programming interface entity mapping. Repository interfaces that write their own structured query language for you. Derived query methods, where Spring inspects the method name and generates the query. The at sign Query annotation for cases derivation cannot reach. Paging and sorting. Transaction boundaries with at sign Transactional. And database migrations with Flyway. After that, notebook eleven brings Spring Boot's production concerns, including auto configuration, actuator, testing, and messaging with Kafka. And notebook twelve finishes the track with Spring Cloud.
